      <body>
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="pra-Latn" rendition="class:83225 maturity:83207">
            <ab part="M"><lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/><unclear>ta</unclear>yasa cetiya<unclear>ṁ</unclear> madhā vetika ca pa<supplied reason="lost">ṭa</supplied><gap reason="lost"/>
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
               <listApp>
                  <app loc="1">
                     <lem><gap reason="illegible" unit="character" quantity="1"/><unclear>ti</unclear>yasa</lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Chanda1919-1920_01 bib:Sivaramamurti1942_01">yasa</rdg>
                  </app>
                  <app loc="1">
                    <lem>cetiya<unclear>ṁ</unclear></lem>
                    <rdg source="bib:Chanda1919-1920_01">cetiya</rdg>
                    <rdg source="bib:Sivaramamurti1942_01">ceti<unclear>ya</unclear></rdg>
                  </app>
                  <app loc="1">
                    <lem>madhā</lem>
                      <rdg source="bib:Chanda1919-1920_01">madhā</rdg>
                      <rdg source="bib:Sivaramamurti1942_01"><unclear>ma</unclear>dhā</rdg>
                      <note>The meaning of this word is unclear at the moment, and the reading is not entirely certain. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Chanda1919-1920_01"/></bibl> suggests it stands for Skt. <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">madhya</foreign>, but one would rather expect <foreign>majha</foreign>. A possible alternative would be <foreign>medhi/medhī</foreign>, meaning a pillar (<ptr target="bib:RhysDavids+Stede1993_01"/>, s.v. <foreign xml:lang="pli-Latn">medhi</foreign>) or a concentric gallery of a <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">stūpa</foreign> (<bibl><ptr target="bib:Edgerton1953_01"/></bibl>, s.v.). As far as we know, this term is however not attested in the epigraphic corpus.</note>
                  </app>
                  <app loc="1">
                      <lem>ca pa<supplied reason="lost">ṭa</supplied></lem>
                      <rdg source="bib:Chanda1919-1920_01">ca<unclear>pa</unclear></rdg>
                      <rdg source="bib:Sivaramamurti1942_01">capa</rdg>
                      <note>The term <foreign>paṭa</foreign> was likely followed by <foreign>deyadhama</foreign>. This reconstruction is supported by <ref target="DHARMA_INSEIAD00274.xml">EIAD 274</ref>.</note>
                  </app>
               </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:argr part:vito">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Pious gift</supplied> of a <foreign>madhā</foreign> and a <foreign>vedikā</foreign> slab for the <placeName type="builtPlace" subtype="shrine">Shrine of</placeName> …</p>
         </div>
